'''Stefan Philip Kruszewski''' is an American [[psychiatrist|clinical]] and [[forensic psychiatrist]]. He is a thrice successful [[Qui tam]] [[relator (law)|relator]].<ref name="Voreacos">Voreacos, David and Margaret Cronin Fisk. AstraZeneca Case Rewards Repeat Whistleblowers With $45 Million [Online]. Bloomberg, L.P. 13 May 2010[Accessed 18 Jul 2011]. Available at: http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-05-12/astrazeneca-s-520-million-u-s-settlement-rewards-repeat-whistleblowers.html</ref> He is principal in the company which bears his name, Stefan P. Kruszewski, M.D. & Associates, P.C.<ref name="Conflicting">Kruszewski SP. Doctors' Conflicting Interests Can Cost Money and Lives, and Hinder Medical Discoveries [Online]. 28 Mar 2011[Accessed 18 Jul 2011]. ABC News.com: Health: Wellness. Available from ABC World News: http://abcnews.go.com/Health/medical-conflicts-interest-disaster-patients/story?id=13060973</ref>

According to his website’s mission statement, Kruszewski says “that medical care is a public trust and that medical practice is an enormous responsibility. Unchecked special interest and commercial [[bias]] in [[medical research]] have undermined both.”<ref>http://www.spkmd.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=56&Itemid=45</ref>

As a fraud investigator for the [[Pennsylvania|Commonwealth of Pennsylvania]] in 2003, Kruszewski uncovered the abuse and medical mistreatment of children and the mentally ill in [[residential treatment center]]s, and was eventually fired for trying to expose what he had discovered.<ref name="Waters">Waters, Rob. "Medicating Aliah." Mother Jones. May/June 2005 Issue. Available at: http://motherjones.com/politics/2005/05/medicating-aliah</ref><ref>Jankovich, Delores MA MSW. "Important Highlights of the 2006 ICSPP Conference." ICSPP Newsletter. 2006. 4: 3-4. Available at: http://psychintegrity.org/storage/newsletter3-pub.pdf</ref> Kruszewski brought suit for [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] claims against the [[Pennsylvania Department of Public Welfare]] and in June 2007 he was awarded a settlement.<ref name="FAsettlement">Stefan P. Kruszewski v Pfizer Inc., et al. Settlement Agreement. No. 04-1420 (United States District Court for the Middle District of Pennsylvania</ref> Also resulting, Kruszewski filed his first Qui tam lawsuit which settled in 2009 against Southwood Psychiatric Hospital.<ref>Hartman, Patty. "U.S. Attorney Announces First Settlement Involving Psychiatric Residential Treatmnet Facilities." United States Attorney's Office, Eastern District, Pennsylvania. 22 Apr 2009. Available at: http://www.justice.gov/usao/pae/News/2009/apr/southwoodrelease.pdf</ref><ref>Marketwire. Fish & Richardson and the U.S. Department of Justice Settle Medicaid Fraud and Abuse Case at Southwood Psychiatric Hospital in Pennsylvania [Online]. SYS-CON Publications, Inc. 23 Apr 2009[Accessed 17 Jul 2011]. Available at: http://au.sys-con.com/node/933956</ref>

He has been a relator in two additional successful Qui tam lawsuits: the first against [[Pfizer]] for its drug [[Ziprasidone|Geodon]] which settled in October 2009,<ref>US Department of Health & Human Services and US Department of Justice. "Pfizer Fact Sheet: Pfizer to pay $2.3 billion to resolve criminal and civil health care liability to fraudulent marketing and the payment of kickbacks"[Online]. StopMedicareFraud.gov. Available at: http://www.stopmedicarefraud.gov/pfizerfactsheet.html</ref><ref>Settlement Agreement Between United States and Pfizer, Inc.[Online]. August 2009. Available at http://www.justice.gov/usao/ma/news/Pfizer/Pfizer%20Settlement%20Agreement.pdf</ref><ref>BBC. Pfizer agrees record fraud fine[online]. 2 Sept 2009. Available at: http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/8234533.stm</ref><ref name="Woolner">Woolner, Ann. AIG of Drugmakers Pfizer is Too Big to Be Guilty [Online]. Bloomberg, L.P. 3 Sept 2009. Available at: http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=ahodmf54hyPA#</ref><ref name="Howard">Howard, Lee. Lawsuit hits credibility of Pfizer drug and research [Online]. The Day Publishing Company. 4 Oct 2009. Available at: http://www.theday.com/article/20091004/BIZ02/310049957</ref><ref name="DrugDisc">Drug Discovery and Development. Pfizer Pays $2 Billion to Settle Off-Label Marketing Case [Online]. Ddmag.com. 2 Sept 2009. Available at: http://www.dddmag.com/news-Pfizer-Pays-2-Billion-to-Settle-Off-Label-Marketing-Case-090209.aspx</ref> and the second against [[AstraZeneca]] for its drug [[Quetiapine|Seroquel]] which settled in April 2010.<ref name="Voreacos" /><ref>Settlement Agreement Between United States and AstraZeneca, Inc.[Online]. April 2010. Available at: http://www.justice.gov/usao/pae/News/2010/apr/astrazeneca_settlementagreement.pdf</ref><ref name="Deming">Deming, Tavy and Brian Kenney. AstraZeneca Pays $520 Million to Settle Seroquel Whistleblower Claims [Online]. PRWeb. 28 Apr 2010[Accessed 17 Jul 2011]. Available at: http://www.prweb.com/releases/2010/04/prweb3937374.htm</ref><ref name="Duff">Wilson, Duff. "Side Effects May Include Lawsuits."[Online]. The New York Times. 2 Oct 2010[Accessed 18 Jul 2011]. Available at: http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/03/business/03psych.html?sq=kruszewski&st=cse&adxnnl=1&scp=1&adxnnlx=1311017427-KiqB MKPXBpWIPBZssV3pw&pagewanted=1</ref>

== Demographics ==
Stefan P. Kruszewski, M.D. was born in [[Queens|Queens County, New York]] and raised in [[Nassau County, New York]] and [[San Antonio, Texas]]. His offices and home are currently in [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]] where he lives with his family. His main avocation is [[oil painting]].

His father, Marion Martin Kruszewski, was a [[dentist]] in [[Maspeth, New York]]. His mother, Frances Joan,<ref>http://www.askart.com/askart/artist.aspx?artist=11165540</ref> was an academic professional [[artist]] who exhibited in [[New York City]] and studied at the [[New School for Social Research]] and [[Art Students League of New York]] with American artists [[Robert Brackman]], George Tschamber, Marian Brown, Paul Puzinas, Edgar Albert Whitney, Anthony Toney, Barbara Vassilieff, [[George Cherepov]] and [[Will Barnet]].

== Education ==
Kruszewski is a graduate of [[the Wheatley School]] in [[Old Westbury, New York]]; [[Princeton University]] in [[Princeton, New Jersey]]; and [[Harvard Medical School]] in [[Boston, Massachusetts]]. He completed post-doctoral education at Harvard Affiliate [[Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center|New England Deaconess Hospital]], Boston, Massachusetts; the [[University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey]]-[[Rutgers University]]/the [[Robert Wood Johnson Medical School]], [[Piscataway, New Jersey|Piscataway]] and [[New Brunswick, New Jersey]]; and [[Duke University]], [[Durham, North Carolina]]. He has been [[board certification|board certified]] in general [[psychiatry]] as well as having been certified in the subspecialties of [[geriatric psychiatry|geriatric]], [[child and adolescent psychiatry|adolescent]] and [[addiction psychiatry]] and, by the [[American Society of Addiction Medicine]], in [[addiction medicine]].

== Career ==
Kruszewski has over 30 years of clinical and teaching experience in the field of psychiatry, with particular focus on addictionology, [[neuropsychiatry]] and [[neuropharmacology]].<ref>Kruszewski's complete resume: http://www.spkmd.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=23&Itemid=40</ref> He has had academic appointments at [[Harvard Medical School]], the University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey-Rutgers University/the Robert Wood Johnson Medical School, Allegheny General Hospital System, [[University of North Texas]], [[University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine]], [[Penn State Milton S. Hershey Medical Center]] and, most recently, [[Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health]].

